1. About Bike Sharing Dataset¶

Data sets include information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area, Los Angeles and Washington DC.

1.1 The greater San Francisco Bay Area¶

  • Service name was changed from Ford GoBike to Bay Wheels at May 2019.
  • There are 12 files in CSV format and each file has a data of whole month of Year 2019.
  • The dataset contains approximately 2.5 million ride information.

1.2 Los Angeles¶

  • Service name is Metro Bike Share.
  • There are 4 files in CSV formation and each file has a data of quarter of Year 2019.
  • The dataset contains approximately 290,000 ride information.

1.3 Washington¶

  • Service name is Capital Bike Share.
  • There are 12 files in CSV format and each file has a data of whole month of Year 2019.
  • The dataset contains approximately 3.4 million ride information.

2.1 Bay Wheels - The greater San Francisco Bay Area - Data¶

  • The service name was changed at May 2019 from Ford GoBike to Bay Wheels.
  • Each file has a riding information for one month.
  • Read files and make them into a single dataframe.
  • File name format
    • 2019mm-fordgobike-tripdata.csv, where mm: 01 ~ 04
    • 2019nn-baywheels-tripdata.csv, where nn: 05 ~ 12
In [2]:

month = ['01', '02', '03', '04', '05', '06', '07', '08', '09', '10', '11', '12']

3.1.4 Summary of Dataset Structure¶

1) Bay Wheels Datasets¶

  • There are approximately 2.5 million trips in the dataset with 15 features.
No column non-null type description
1 duration_sec 2,506,983 int64 duration of trip in seconds
2 start_time 2,506,983 object start date and time
3 end_time 2,506,983 object end date and time
4 start_station_id 2,426,249 float64 ID of start station
5 start_station_name 2,426,850 object name of start station
6 start_station_latitude 2,506,983 float64 latitude of start station
7 start_station_longitude 2,506,983 float64 longitude of start station
8 end_station_id 2,424,081 float64 ID of end station
9 end_station_name 2,424,633 object name of end station
10 end_station_latitude 2,506,983 float64 latitude of end station
11 end_station_longitude 2,506,983 float64 longigude of end station
12 bike_id 2,506,983 int64 ID of bike
13 user_type 2,506,983 object Type of user, Subscriber (member) or Customer (temporary)
14 bike_share_for_all_trip 2,263,724 object Yes or No.
15 rental_access_method 120,838 object This feature found in June, July and November. The value is either app or clipper

2) Metro Datasets¶

  • There are approximately 290K trips in the dataset with 15 features.
No column non-null type description
1 trip_id 290,342 int64 ID of trip
2 duration 290,342 int64 length of trip in minutes
3 start_time 290,342 object start date and time
4 end_time 290,342 object end date and time
5 start_station 290,342 int64 start station ID
6 start_lat 285,505 float64 latitude of start station
7 start_lon 285,505 float64 longitude of start station
8 end_station 290,342 int64 end station ID
9 end_lat 279,757 float64 latitude of end station
10 end_lon 279,757 float64 longitude of end station
11 bike_id 290,342 object ID of bike
12 plan_duration 290,342 int64 The number of days that the plan the passholder is using entitles them to ride; 0 is used for a single ride plan (Walk-up); 999 is used for testing purpose.
13 trip_route_category 290,342 object Round Trip or One Way
14 passholder_type 290,342 object The name of the passholder's plan
15 bike_type 290,342 object The kind of bike used on the trip, including standard pedal-powered bikes, electric assist bikes, or smart bikes.

3) Capital Datasets¶

  • There are approximately 3.4 million trips in the dataset with 9 features.
No column non-null type description
1 Duration 3,398,417 int64 duration of trip in minute
2 Start date 3,398,417 object start date and time
3 End date 3,398,417 object end date and time
4 Start station number 3,398,417 int64 ID of start station
5 Start station 3,398,417 object start station location
6 End station number 3,398,417 int64 ID of end station
7 End station 3,398,417 object end station location
8 Bike number 3,398,403 object ID of bike
9 Member type 3,398,417 object Indicates whether user was a "registered" member (Annual Member, 30-Day Member or Day Key Member) or a "casual" rider (Single Trip, 24-Hour Pass, 3-Day Pass or 5-Day Pass)

3.5 Quality Issues¶

1) Bay Wheels (formerly Ford GoBike) Table¶

  • start_time and end_time: erroneous data types, should be datetime type
  • start_station_id, end_station_id, bike_id: These fields do not require arithmetic operation.
  • rental_access_method: 3 out of 12 files have this feature. We can found feature at June, July and November. It should be category type.
  • start_station_id: missing values in 80,734 rows
  • end_station_id: missing values in 82,902 rows
  • user_type: This field is object type (string). Only two kinds of values are possbile. It should be category type.
  • bike_share_for_all_trip: 243,259 null values and it should be category type. However, there is no description for this feature. The meaning of this variable is not clear.

2) Metro Bike Share Table¶

  • start_time, end_time: erroneous data types, should be datetime type
  • start_station, end_station: erroneous data types, should be string type
  • start_lat, start_lon, end_lat, end_lon: missing values
  • plan_duration: 999 for test
  • passholder_type: object type. It should be categorical type. Value of Testing is not a valid user.
  • trip_route_category and bike_type: It should be categorical type.

3) Capital Bike Share Table¶

  • Start date, End date: erroneous data types, should be datetime type
  • Start station number and End station number: erroneous data types, should be string type
  • Bike number: missing values, 14 rows have null value
  • Member type: It should be category type
  • column names are not proper to handle. Some of the column names contains space (' ') in their name.

3.6 Tidiness Issues¶

  • The number of features and their meaning are different. Washington (Capital Bike Share) dataset has 9 features and the otheer two datasets have 15 features.
    • Common features (meaning or data contains): duration, start time, end time, start station id, end station id, bike id, and user type

4.4 Qaulity Issues: Erroneous Data Types of the Variables¶

1) Define¶

Date and time features¶
  • start_time and end_time from Bay Wheels: It should be datetime type
  • start_time and end_time from Metro: It should be datetime type
  • start_date and end_date: It should be datetime type
  • Change the data type of above features to datetime type using pandas to_datetime()
IDs¶
  • start_station_id, end_station_id and bike_id from Bay Wheels: It should be string type
  • start_station and end_station from Metro: It should be string type
  • start_station_number and end_station_number from Capital: It should be string type
  • Change data type of above features to string using astype() function.
  • For Bay Wheels, station id is float type. Values of station id are ended with '.0'. Remove ending '.0' using strip function.
User Type¶
  • user_type, bike_share_for_all_trip,and rental_access_method from Bay Wheels: It should be category type.
  • trip_route_category, passholder_type, and bike_type from Metro: It should be category type. Value of Testing is not a valid user.
  • member_type from Capital: It should be catory type.
  • change data type of above features to category type using astype("category").

Dataset Structure¶

  • Bike share dataset has approximately 6 millions of trip records of three cities with 8 features (duration, start time, end time, start station id, end station id, bike id, user type and city).
  • Description of columns
No column non-null type description
0 duration 6,095,891 int64 Trip duration in minute
1 start_time 6,095,891 datetime64 The date/time when the trip began.
2 end_time 6,095,891 datetime64 The date/time when the trip ended.
3 start_station_id 6,095,891 object The station ID where the trip originated.
4 end_station_id 6,095,891 object The station ID where the trip terminated.
5 bike_id 6,095,891 object bike ID
6 user_type 6,095,891 category Type of user
7 city 6,095,891 category San Francisco, Los Angeles, and Washington DC

Main features of interest¶

  • I'm most interested in the following:
    • The relation between bike demand and time, day of week and user type
    • What time is the most demands?
    • What day of the week is the modst demands?
    • What is difference of pattern of demands by user type?

Features that support investigation into features of interest¶

  • I expect high demands in the morning time between 7 to 9 on weekday in the downtown area. However, demands on weekends will be different from the demand on weekday.
  • The demands of bike will be similar in three cities.

Note: The differences in the number of trip information from the three cities are severely different. Especially, the Metro bike share has about 290K cases and it is only 4.8% of the dataset. For this reason, overall trends may mislead the results. To avoid misleading analyses by cities are required.¶

6.2 Parse and Categorizing¶

6.2.1 Parse datetime features: start_time and end_time¶

  • Parse start_time and end_time to month, date, day of the week, hour, and minute
  • Add column for indicating working day or not (weekends)
In [61]:
# start_time
bike_share['start_month'] = bike_share['start_time'].dt.month
bike_share['start_date'] = bike_share['start_time'].dt.day
bike_share['start_hour'] = bike_share['start_time'].dt.hour
bike_share['start_minute'] = bike_share['start_time'].dt.minute
bike_share['start_day'] = bike_share['start_time'].dt.day_name()

# end_time
bike_share['end_month'] = bike_share['end_time'].dt.month
bike_share['end_date'] = bike_share['end_time'].dt.day
bike_share['end_hour'] = bike_share['end_time'].dt.hour
bike_share['end_minute'] = bike_share['end_time'].dt.minute
bike_share['end_day'] = bike_share['end_time'].dt.day_name()

# change type of start_day and end_day to category
bike_share['start_day'] = bike_share['start_day'].astype("category")
bike_share['end_day'] = bike_share['end_day'].astype("category")
day_of_week = ['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday', 'Sunday']
bike_share['start_day'] = pd.Categorical(bike_share['start_day'], categories=day_of_week, ordered=True)


# working day or not
work_day_of_week = ['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday']
bike_share['working_day'] = bike_share['start_day'].isin(work_day_of_week)
bike_share['working_day'] = bike_share['working_day'].astype("category")

Finding (2)¶

  • The plot for the demands by month for the whole dataset shows that the demands drop in the cold-weather seasons from Nov to Feb.
  • However, the demands by cities have different patterns.
  • In San Francisco, the demands from Jan, Feb, May, Jun, July, and Nov are similar. Dec is the lowest demand month and the highest demand is in Mar.
  • In Los Angeles, the demands from Jan to May are similar and demands from Nov and Dec are higher than Apr or May. August is the highest demand, and February is the lowest.
  • In Washington DC, high demands from April to October but, the demands of bikes drop in the winter season. The demands in Washington DC increased as getting warmer and decrease as getting cold.
  • Further study and more data are needed to understand the demand pattern of the cities.

Finding (7)¶

  • For San Francisco:
    • The average trip durations on weekdays are between 11 and 14 minutes regardless of months.
    • The average trip durations on weekends are about 5 to 6 minutes longer than weekdays and the average trip duration is between 16 and 20 minutes regardless of months.
    • In the cold-weather season of Dec, Jan, and Feb, the average trip durations on weekends are about 14 to 16 minutes, which are lower than other months.
  • For Los Angeles:
    • The average trip durations are longer than San Francisco and their values are mostly between 24 and 36.
    • On weekends, the average trip durations are over 40 minutes from Jan to Aug.
  • For Washington DC:
    • The average trip durations on weekdays are slightly wide range than in San Francisco. The distribution of the average trip duration is between 12 and 19 minutes.
    • On weekends, average trip durations are longer than weekdays like the other two cities. The range of average trip duration is from 17 to 27 minutes.
    • In cold-weather seasons from Nov to Feb, the average trip durations are 2 to 5 minutes shorter than the other months.
  • Overall, the average trip duration on weekends is longer than weekdays.
  • During the cold-weather season, the average trip durations are a little bit lower than other seasons.
  • The differences in the average trip duration of the cities require further study.

But further study to find the answer why the demands from casual users are steady and different pattern of use.

6.6 Opinions¶

6.6.1 About the relationships observed¶

At the beginning of the analysis, I focused on the demands of a bike, and my investigation was extended to the trip duration and user type. I expected the demand patterns of the three cities are similar to each other. However, I found that the patterns of demands are different in several ways. The plots of the demands by weekdays showed San Francisco had about 1.9 times more demands on weekdays, in contrast, bike demands in Los Angeles and Washington DC on weekdays are about 21% or less than weekdays. Demands by time, the most demanding time on weekdays and weekends were quite different. The graph for the number of trips by months illustrated in some area demands was related to temperature like Washington DC. But, the demands by months were not the same pattern of average temperature in those cities. For the trip duration, generally, trip duration on weekends was longer than weekdays. The average trip duration was also different in each city, it might be related to geographic features of the cities and the number of stations. Multivariate exploration showed trip duration did not match the average temperature of the cities. With multivariate exploration on user type, I guess that subscribers used the service to commute to work and casual users' demands increased on weekends.

6.6.2 Require Further Study¶

Interestingly, the demands pattern are not the same in the three cities and followed the average temperature. I found the demands of the bike are different but I did not have the reasons why different. I thought the usage of bike-sharing services is almost similar regardless of location or cities, but the investigation results presented they were not. Further study might require weather data such as temperature, raining, or snowing and station location. I did not use coordinates for the analysis, but they might give me an answer for the trip duration.
